      "text": "He emphasizes that in his correspondence with Einstein, Freud did not name an \"aggression instinct\" as the reason for wars, but rather the selfish, self-serving interests of those in power. Only in the second part of his argument did he refer to biological conditions, but not in order to explain the motivation of those in power, but rather the willingness of millions of people to allow themselves to be killed or to kill others for these selfish goals. Mentzos considers this explanation to be wrong, \"firstly because there are many more motivations for participating in war than aggression, and secondly because this aggression, insofar as it is involved, is not based on an endogenous, energetically conceived drive (let alone: death drive), but arises from external and intrapsychic conflicts.\""
