        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "e8e84c88d31def33",
        "text": "To summarize the various psychoanalytical concepts, it can be said that power holders or those who strive for power use interaction and communication with others to satisfy their narcissistic needs, live out their fantasies of grandeur and overcome their depression of separation. The opportunities associated with the status of the powerful to enter into a quasi-causal relationship with other people – one commands, the other obeys – are experienced and enjoyed as an extension of one's own self and thus as overcoming its limits. The inclusion of a social system in the self-definition seemingly enables the resolution of the paradox of self-control, which is linked to the necessity of communication with others and the limitation of the possibilities of control to self-control (the alternative is autism, i.e. the breaking off of all communication). The resolution of the paradox is apparent because – viewed from an external perspective – the control of the social system as an autopoietic system does not succeed. In the best case, a do-as-if pattern emerges in which a person in power is presented with the image of themselves and others that they would like to see, without this having anything to do with the actual reality of the social system (cf. the \"Erich Honecker syndrome\")56.\n"
      },
      "date": 1710412625745
    },
